To update a table in flash memory of STM32L072, you need to follow a few steps. Below is the general procedure to update flash memory on STM32L072:

1. First, you need to define your table and its structure in the code.

   For example, you could define a table as an array of structures:

   ```
   typedef struct
   {
     uint8_t variable1;
     uint16_t variable2;
     uint32_t variable3;
   } myTableStruct;

   myTableStruct myTable[] =
   {
     { 0x01, 0x1234, 0xABCDABCD },
     { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
     ...
   };
   ```

2. Next, you need to determine where the table will be located in flash memory. 

   To do this, you can use a linker script for your project that specifies the memory layout of the microcontroller. You would set aside a portion of the flash memory for your table.

3. Then, you would copy the entire updated table into a temporary buffer in RAM. 

   You would make modifications to the updated table in the RAM buffer.

4. Next, you would erase the corresponding sector of flash memory where the table is located.

   You can use `HAL_FLASH_Erase` function from STM32 HAL library to erase the corresponding sector.

5. Finally, you would write the updated table data to the erased flash memory.

   You can use `HAL_FLASH_Program` function from STM32 HAL library to write the updated table data to the erased flash memory.

Note that updating a table in flash memory requires careful consideration of memory boundaries and flash wear. Therefore, it is important to follow the best practices outlined in the STM32L072 data sheets and documentation, as well as good software engineering practices.

Here is some example C code that demonstrates how to update a table in flash memory on an STM32L072 microcontroller:

```c
#include "stm32l072xx.h"

typedef struct
{
  uint8_t variable1;
  uint16_t variable2;
  uint32_t variable3;
} myTableStruct;

// Define the table in a specific location in flash memory
__attribute__((section(".myTableSection"))) myTableStruct myTable[] =
{
  { 0x01, 0x1234, 0xABCDABCD },
  { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
  // ...
};

int main(void)
{
  // Define an updated table
  myTableStruct updatedTable[] =
  {
    { 0x01, 0x1234, 0x12345678 },  // Modify variable3 in the first element
    { 0x02, 0x5678, 0x87654321 },
    // ...
  };

  // Calculate the size of the updated table
  size_t updatedTableSize = sizeof(updatedTable);

  // Copy the updated table into a temporary buffer
  uint8_t buffer[updatedTableSize];
  memcpy(buffer, updatedTable, updatedTableSize);

  // Unlock the flash memory for writing
  HAL_FLASH_Unlock();

  // Erase the sector where the table is located
  FLASH_Erase_Sector(FLASH_SECTOR_3, VOLTAGE_RANGE_3);

  // Get the start address of the flash memory location for the table
  uint32_t flashTableAddress = (uint32_t)&myTable;

  // Write the updated table to flash memory
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i += 2)
  {
    uint16_t data = buffer[i] | (buffer[i+1] << 8);
    HAL_FLASH_Program(FLASH_TYPEPROGRAM_HALFWORD, flashTableAddress + i, data);
  }

  // Lock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Lock();

  // ...
}
```

This code assumes that a linker script has been created that defines a memory section for the table, and places it in the desired location in flash memory. The `__attribute__((section(".myTableSection")))` attribute is used to place the table in the correct section.

The code defines an updated table and copies it into a temporary buffer. It then erases the flash sector where the table is located, and writes the updated table data to the flash memory location for the table. Finally, the flash memory is locked again to prevent accidental writes.

To change the code to make the table configurable, you could modify the code to read the table data from an external source, such as an external flash memory IC, or use a communication protocol that allows the microcontroller to receive and store table data from an external device or system.

For example, you could use an SPI flash memory IC to store the table data, and use the SPI interface on the STM32L072 to read the table data from the IC. Here is some example C code that demonstrates how you might modify the previous code to read the table data from an external SPI flash memory IC:

```c
#include "stm32l072xx.h"
#include "spi.h"    // External SPI interface driver

typedef struct
{
  uint8_t variable1;
  uint16_t variable2;
  uint32_t variable3;
} myTableStruct;

// Define the table in a specific location in flash memory
__attribute__((section(".myTableSection"))) myTableStruct myTable[] =
{
  { 0x01, 0x1234, 0xABCDABCD },
  { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
  // ...
};

int main(void)
{
  // Read the updated table from external SPI flash memory
  myTableStruct updatedTable[10];
  uint32_t tableAddress = 0x00001000;   // Memory address of table in external SPI flash
  SPI_ReadData(tableAddress, (uint8_t *)updatedTable, sizeof(updatedTable));

  // Calculate the size of the updated table
  size_t updatedTableSize = sizeof(updatedTable);

  // Copy the updated table into a temporary buffer
  uint8_t buffer[updatedTableSize];
  memcpy(buffer, updatedTable, updatedTableSize);

  // Unlock the flash memory for writing
  HAL_FLASH_Unlock();

  // Erase the sector where the table is located
  FLASH_Erase_Sector(FLASH_SECTOR_3, VOLTAGE_RANGE_3);

  // Get the start address of the flash memory location for the table
  uint32_t flashTableAddress = (uint32_t)&myTable;

  // Write the updated table to flash memory
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i += 2)
  {
    uint16_t data = buffer[i] | (buffer[i+1] << 8);
    HAL_FLASH_Program(FLASH_TYPEPROGRAM_HALFWORD, flashTableAddress + i, data);
  }

  // Lock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Lock();

  // ...
}
```

In this code, the `SPI_ReadData` function is used to read the updated table data from an external SPI flash memory IC. The data is then written to the target memory location in the STM32L072 internal flash memory.

Note that in this example, the size of the updated table is set to 10, and the memory address of the table in the external SPI flash is set to 0x00001000. These values should be modified to match the size and memory address of the table stored in the external memory device.

To update the table in flash memory based on data coming from ADC that are stored in SRAM (1KB), you could modify the code to read the updated table data from the SRAM buffer instead of an external source. Here is some example C code that demonstrates how to implement this approach:

```c
#include "stm32l072xx.h"
#include "adc.h"    // ADC driver

typedef struct
{
  uint8_t variable1;
  uint16_t variable2;
  uint32_t variable3;
} myTableStruct;

myTableStruct myTable[] =
{
  { 0x01, 0x1234, 0xABCDABCD },
  { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
  // ...
};

int main(void)
{
  // Read ADC data into SRAM buffer
  uint8_t adcData[1024];
  ADC_ReadData(adcData, sizeof(adcData));

  // Process ADC data and update table in SRAM
  size_t updatedTableSize = sizeof(myTable);
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i++)
  {
    myTable[i].variable3 = adcData[i * 2] | (adcData[i * 2 + 1] << 8);
  }

  // Unlock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Unlock();

  // Erase the sector where the table is located
  FLASH_Erase_Sector(FLASH_SECTOR_3, VOLTAGE_RANGE_3);

  // Get the start address of the flash memory location for the table
  uint32_t flashTableAddress = (uint32_t)&myTable;

  // Write the updated table data to flash memory
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i += 2)
  {
    uint16_t data = (uint16_t)(myTable[i].variable1) | ((uint16_t)(myTable[i].variable2) << 8);
    HAL_FLASH_Program(FLASH_TYPEPROGRAM_HALFWORD, flashTableAddress + i, data);
  }

  // Lock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Lock();

  // ...
}
```

In this example code, we read the ADC data into an SRAM buffer using an `ADC_ReadData` function that might be implemented using the STM32 ADC driver library. We then use this data to update the existing table in SRAM based on certain logic. Finally, we write this updated table data into the Flash sector using the HAL_FLASH_Program function.

Note that, in this example, the size of the table is set to sizeof(myTable) and the size of the ADC buffer is set to 1024 bytes, assuming that each element in the table fits within two bytes. If your table structure contains variables that fit into a single byte or variables that require more than two bytes, you may need to modify the size of the table or update the code logic for writing the updated data to Flash correctly.

If each sample from the ADC is 32 bits, you would need to modify the code to account for this larger data size. Here is some example C code that demonstrates how to modify the previous code to handle the larger 32-bit sample size:

```c
#include "stm32l072xx.h"
#include "adc.h"    // ADC driver

typedef struct
{
  uint8_t variable1;
  uint16_t variable2;
  uint32_t variable3;
} myTableStruct;

myTableStruct myTable[] =
{
  { 0x01, 0x1234, 0xABCDABCD },
  { 0x02, 0x5678, 0xEFEFEFEF },
  // ...
};

int main(void)
{
  // Read ADC data into SRAM buffer
  uint8_t adcData[2048];
  ADC_ReadData(adcData, sizeof(adcData));

  // Process ADC data and update table in SRAM
  size_t updatedTableSize = sizeof(myTable);
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i++)
  {
    myTable[i].variable3 = (uint32_t)(adcData[i * 4]) |
                           ((uint32_t)(adcData[i * 4 + 1]) << 8) |
                           ((uint32_t)(adcData[i * 4 + 2]) << 16) |
                           ((uint32_t)(adcData[i * 4 + 3]) << 24);
  }

  // Unlock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Unlock();

  // Erase the sector where the table is located
  FLASH_Erase_Sector(FLASH_SECTOR_3, VOLTAGE_RANGE_3);

  // Get the start address of the flash memory location for the table
  uint32_t flashTableAddress = (uint32_t)&myTable;

  // Write the updated table data to flash memory
  for (size_t i = 0; i < updatedTableSize; i += 2)
  {
    uint16_t dataLow = (uint16_t)(myTable[i].variable1) | ((uint16_t)(myTable[i].variable2) << 8);
    uint16_t dataHigh = (uint16_t)(myTable[i].variable3 & 0xFFFF) | ((uint16_t)((myTable[i].variable3 >> 16) & 0xFFFF) << 8);
    HAL_FLASH_Program(FLASH_TYPEPROGRAM_HALFWORD, flashTableAddress + i, dataLow);
    HAL_FLASH_Program(FLASH_TYPEPROGRAM_HALFWORD, flashTableAddress + i + 2, dataHigh);
  }

  // Lock the flash memory
  HAL_FLASH_Lock();

  // ...
}
```
